post_text: Congratulations, Senator DiDomenico!
shared_text:
State Senator Sal DiDomenico
August 17 at 6:16 PM ¬∑

It was an honor to recently accept the 2020 Breakfast Hero award from the national anti-hunger campaign No Kid Hungry. Being one of just six recipients throughout the United States to receive this award, coupled with the Governor signing my Breakfast After the Bell bill into law earlier this month, made this recognition particularly special.

I am thrilled that we were able to get Breakfast After the Bell across the finish line this session for the thousands of kids across the Commonwealth who are in need of a nutritious start to their days. I firmly believe that we can have the best teachers, facilities, and technology in our classrooms, but if our kids are showing up for school hungry, they simply cannot be ready to learn. Thank you to No Kid Hungry for this recognition- I truly could not have done it without the help and advocacy of so many incredible organizations!

post_text: Important safety information from the Mayor:
shared_text:
Mayor Carlo DeMaria
July 28 at 11:16 AM ¬∑

üî• TIPS FOR STAYING SAFE DURING HEAT ADVISORY üî•

Drink plenty of fluids, stay in an air-conditioned room, stay out of the sun, and check up on relatives and neighbors.

Young children and pets should never be left unattended in vehicles under any circumstances.

Take extra precautions if you work or spend time outside. When possible reschedule strenuous activities to early morning or evening. Know the signs and symptoms of heat exhaustion and heat stroke. Wear lightweight and loose fitting clothing when possible.

To reduce risk during outdoor work, the Occupational
Safety and Health Administration recommends scheduling frequent rest breaks in shaded or air conditioned environments. Anyone overcome by heat should be moved to a cool and shaded location.

Heat stroke is an emergency! Call 9 1 1.

post_text: Great news from the Mayor's Office!
shared_text:
Mayor Carlo DeMaria
July 1 at 12:33 PM ¬∑

It is with great pleasure that I announce this year's Crimson Kid's program will be back!

It has been a long break this far for our kids and parents! I'm thrilled that our City has been able to work out the logistics to offer this great program to our residents!

Applications will be accepted beginning Monday, July 6th at 10:00AM at the Everett Community Health & Wellness Center. At this time, because of the guidelines set forth by the state, we will be able to accept 70 children per week. Please note, spots will be available on a first come, first serve, basis.

‚ô¶Camp will begin on Monday July 13th

‚ô¶The cost is $75 for the first child, per week, and $25 any additional child.

‚ô¶$25 per child per week, is due at time of sign up, as a non- refundable deposit.

‚ô¶Payments will be accepted via credit card only and due at the time of registration.

‚ô¶All paperwork is needed at time of sign up, before the child can be enrolled.

Printable applications can be found here:
http://www.cityofeverett.com/DocumentCenter/View/6006/2020-Everett-Summer-Program-Registration-1?bidId=

post_text:
STATEMENT ON GRADUATION PLANNING

"EPS is moving quickly but carefully toward holding our drive through graduation ceremony. To make this a reality, the district must adhere to mandatory safety precautions recently issued by the Department of Elementary and Secondary Education. The guidelines require intense and detailed planning by school and city officials. But we're making progress with this cooperative effort. In fact, Everett just successfully completed an extra approval process in our steps to make live graduation a reality. We look forward to sharing more details on our drive through commencement before the end of this week."
-Priya Tahiliani

Good Morning Last night was going to be the Annual Memorial Day Tribute Concert that was started by Mr Kelleher nearly 30 years ago at the Centre School in Everett. But thanks to the hard work of Charlotte Grande and Penny Yebba a Program was printed with all the student names and music selections. Not all has been lost.
This weekend is Memorial Day please say thank you to a Veteran and for this year our front line workers of EMTs Nurses Doctors custodians Police Fire.

post_text:
THE YOUNG AT ART

A collection of striking artwork by Keverian School students is currently on display on the second floor of the administration building on Vine Street. Under the direction of teacher Caroline DiCicco, the students have been working to utilize line shape, value, proportion, color, and texture in a variety of ways. The works on display here include observational drawing, portraiture, surrealism, cartooning, illustration, landscape, and design.

HOGWARTS HAS NOTHING ON THE KEVERIAN!

The Superintendent talked to the students about some of themes relevant to the reading and shared with them her personal affection for the Harry Potter books as both a reader and a former middle school teacher.

At right, the Superintendent is pictured with Principal Alex Naumann and Assistant Principal Janet Taylor.

post_text: The Everett Public Schools joins the Mayor in extending its condolences the McGrath Family.
shared_text:
Mayor Carlo DeMaria
February 26 at 3:22 PM ¬∑

My family and I are saddened by the loss of our friend and local sports announcer, Jack McGrath. Jack was a longtime Everett legend who was dedicated to sports, his family, and the City of Everett. The press box at Everett Stadium will now and forever be known as the Jack McGrath press box.

His knowledge of Everett sports was remarkable, but his greatest attribute was his kindness and compassion for others; especially Everett‚Äôs youth.

Thank you, Jack, for all you did for our community. You will be sorely missed.

shared_text:
State Senator Sal DiDomenico
February 4 at 6:00 PM ¬∑

Incredible turnout at today‚Äôs Lift Our Kids MA Coalition‚Äôs event to collect shoes and socks for families in need! Representative Marjorie Decker and I, working in partnership with the Lift MA Kids coalition, are the lead sponsors of legislation to lift families out of deep poverty. The term deep poverty applies to families living below half the federal poverty line. To illustrate, this equates to only $905 for a family of 3. It is unconscionable that we have 50,000 children living so far below the poverty line in our Commonwealth. Far too often, children living in deep poverty go without the basic items they need, including things like shoes and socks. We can‚Äì and must‚Äì do better, and we can start by passing S.36/H.102 this legislative session.

We are fortunate to have so many co-sponsors in both the House and Senate, I would like to thank the many elected officials and advocacy organizations who attended and donated at today‚Äôs event!

The term deep poverty applies to families living below half the federal poverty line. To illustrate, this equates to only $905 for a family of 3. It is unconscionable that we have 50,000 children living so far below the poverty line in our Commonwealth. Far too often, children living in deep poverty go without the basic items they need, including things like shoes and socks. We can‚Äì and must‚Äì do better, and we can start by passing S.36/H.102 this legislative session.

We are fortunate to have so many co-sponsors in both the House and Senate, I would like to thank the many elected officials and advocacy organizations who attended and donated at today‚Äôs event!
